section.Text:
##### Component in Corporate UI

  1. To create a new component you need to go your forked **sdds** folder. If it is a modular / standalone components such as buttons, alert, then create it under `sdds/components/src/components`. But if it is a complex component that consist of several different modular components, create it under `sdds/components/src/patterns`


  2. Create a new file called the same as your component, make it a **.tsx** file


  3. Go to the your components .tsx file and import the core function for component called `Components` and `h` 

  ```Javascript
    import { Component, h } from '@stencil/core';
  ```


  4. Now it is time to name your component, add the following line below the import. The `tag` property is where you need the component you are creating. We have rule when naming, you need to use a "c-" before the component name.

  ```Javascript
  @Component({
    tag:'c-new-component' // Name of the component <c-new-component>
  })
  ```


  5. Next step is to add the class for the component. Create a class and export it.

  ```Javascript
    export class NewComponent {
        //Component
    }
  ```


  6. Inside the class add the `render()` function, this is where you return your elements HTML structure. Inside the `render()` you return a tree structure of your component. You **need ** to have the html nested inside a parent element on highest level, and you can't have two on the highest level.

   ```Javascript
    export class NewComponent {
      // Add Render()
      render() {
        return(
          // Add your HTML inside the return
          <div>
              Cool Component!
          </div>
        )
      }
    }
  ```


  7. Create a storybook to preview your component

  ```Javascript
    import readme from './readme.md';

  export default {
    title: 'Components/NewComponent',
    parameters: {
      notes: readme,
    },
  };
  ```


  8. For the default (non-scania) styling you need to add a another file called `new-component.scss`. This file will contain all non related styling that might come with the component. This styling will follow the component even if you don't use the scania-theme. Keep this file in the same folder as your component `src/components/"new-component"/`. For example a component that should have a dropdown function might be able to use bootstraps global dropdown css. That should be in this file then.

  ```Javascript
    @Component({
      tag:'c-new-component',
      styleUrl: 'new-component.scss'
      })
  ```


  9. Inside the `@Component` decorator you need to add another property called `shadow: true`. This will make the component isolated and not effected by the reset of the global styling.

  ```Javascript
    @Component({
      tag:'c-new-component',
      styleUrl: 'new-component.scss',
      shadow: true
    })
  ```


  10. How to add properties,states or watches you can look at the stencil documentation. Here is an example of a hello world component.

  ```Javascript
    // Example component
    import { Component, h, Prop } from '@stencil/core';

    @Component({
      tag: 'c-new-component',
      styleUrl: 'new-component.scss',
      shadow: true,
    })
    export class NewComponent {
      @Prop() text: string = 'Hello World';

      render() {
        return (
          <div>
            <h2>{this.text} component</h2>
          </div>
        );
      }
    }
  ```

If you have done everything correctly you should see the component in Action without any specific styling, otherwise check of errors or see if everything is imported and linked correctly. You can see the "Problems that might appear" section

sYou can use SDDS colour scale in your Javascript application by importing the SASS file or use the ready-made CSS custom properties and classes.


**SASS**

We have a ready-to-use function to help you get the colour from SDDS colour library. Remember, you need to install `node-sass` in your application.

```
// First, import the main file in your sass file
@import '~node_modules/@scania/colour/dist/scss/colour';

// use a function called get-colour(token-name) to get colour from SDDS colour scale
.my-div {
  color: get-colour(blue-900);
}

// The code will be rendered as below
.my-div {
  color: #041E42;
}
```

**CSS classes and CSS Custom Properties**

All colours are available if you install scania-theme and add sdds-theme component. 

```<sdds-theme  name="scania"></sdds-theme>```

Or, if you do not use scania-theme, you can import the main css from @scania/colour into your main css file. 
Then, you are ready to use the available classes and CSS variables in your CSS or HTML. Available properties for CSS classes are background and text colour. The format of CSS variables and classes, are always started with prefix `sdds-`.

```
// On your CSS file
// You don't need to do this if you use scania-theme
@import '~node_modules/@scania/colour/dist/css/colour.css';

.my-text{
   color: var(--sdds-blue-900);
}
```

In HTML file:

```
// Use this to style your element
// .sdds-{property}-{token-name}

<p class="sdds-text-blue-900 sdds-background-grey-200">
  An example paragraph
</p>

```

You can use SDDS typography tokens in your Javascript application by importing the SASS file or use the ready-made CSS custom properties and classes.

You need to include the font-face CSS *only if* you do not install '@scania/theme-light'.
You can add it from the package or from the CDN.

```
@import '~node_modules/@scania/typography/dist/fonts/scania-sans.css';

// OR

@import url('https://cdn.digitaldesign.scania.com/fonts/scania-sans/1.0.0/scania-sans.css');
```

**SASS**

We have a ready-to-use function to help you get the typography from SDDS library. Remember, you need to install `node-sass` in your application.

```
// First, import mixin and tokens file in your SASS environment
@import '~node_modules/@scania/typography/dist/scss/mixins';
@import '~node_modules/@scania/typography/dist/scss/tokens';

// use a mixin called type-style(token-name) to get typography properties from SDDS
.my-headline {
    @include type-style('headline-01');
}

// The code will be rendered as below
.my-headline {
  font-family: "Scania Sans Headline", Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
  font-weight: bold;
  font-size: 10rem;
  line-height: 10rem;
  letter-spacing: 0em;
}
```

**CSS classes**

The format of CSS class is `sdds-{token-name}`.

In HTML file:

```
<p class="sdds-headline-01">
  This is a headline
</p>

```

